Description: Topsmelt is a small fish species found in bays and estuaries, among other coastal ecosystems. This species is targeted by commercial fisheries but is considered to have a stable population size.
Caption: Topsmelt Silverside on towel.
ImageLiscence: Free to copy and adapt with credit

Description: Shiner surfperch are non-migratory fish that live in marine and brackish (slightly salty, occuring where salt and fresh water meet) waters. There are small commercial fisheries that target this species, and it is occasionally used as bait by recreational fishers. This species is vulnerable to habitat loss.
Caption: Shiner Surfperch swimming.
ImageLiscence: Free to copy and adapt with credit

Description: Diamond Turbot is a type of flatfish that occurs in coastal and brackish waters, living on muddy and sandy bottoms. They are not commercially targeted, but some recreational fishers may target this specices. It is not considered to be vulnerable.
Caption: Windowpane flounder laying on table. Similar species to Diamond turbot.
ImageLiscence: Free to copy and adapt with credit

Description: California Halibut is a large species of flatfish that lives on the Pacific Coast of the United States. This species is targeted by both commercial and recreational fisheries. It is considered to be vulnerable to the loss of critical nursery habitat.
Caption: Three men standing next two many of the California Halibut that they caught.
ImageLiscence: Free to copy and adapt with credit

Description: Leopard sharks are a small species of shark that lives in shallow waters in the Pacific Coast of the United States. It is targeted by both commercial and recreational fisheries, and is susceptible to overfishing.
Caption: Leopard shark in sand.
ImageLiscence: Free to copy and adapt with credit

Description: The American Avocet is a migrating bird that occurs in the Western half of the United States. This bird is generally stable but is vulnerable to climate change impacts, especially in their salt marsh habitats.
Caption: Two American Avocets standing in water.
ImageLiscence: Free to copy and adapt with credit

Description: Belted Kingfishers are common, migrating birds that occur across North America. Recent surveys indicate a decline in population, as these birds tend to be vulnerable to habitat loss and climate change.
Caption: Belted Kingfisher sitting on tree branch above water.

Description: The Bonaparte's Gull is the smallest gull to occur in North America and migrates from Canada to coastal United States in the winter. While it is vulnerable to climate change and increased temperatures, it is less vulnerable to other human-related disturbances.
Caption: Bonaparte's Gull standing on branch.

Description: Great Blue Herons are large, common water birds and are considered to be highly adaptable. They will likely not be negatively affected by climate change.
Caption: Great Blue Heron flying over water.

Description: Great Egrets are a tall, water bird that is generally not vulnerable to climate change. This bird has a wide range that spans the Southern pacific and Southern Atlantic coasts of the United States.
Caption: Great Egret flying.

Description: The Green Heron is smaller than the Great Blue Heron but will also likely not be impacted negatively by climate change.
Caption: Green Heron standing on rock.

Description: The Mew Gull, also known as the Common Gull, is a medium-sized, migrating water bird that is common along the Pacific Coast and in Alaska and Northern Canada. Like many other birds, the Mew Gull is vulnerable to pollution.
Caption: Mew Gull standing near water.

Description: The Pied-billed Grebe is a common and widespread bird. While there have been declines in this species in the last few decades, it is generally not vulnerable to disturbances.
Caption: Pied-billed Grebe swimming in water.
ImageLiscence: Free to copy and adapt with credit

Description: The Red-breasted Merganser is a species of duck found in coastal United States and the Great Lakes Region. This species may lose about 30% of its range due to climate change.
Caption: Red-breasted Merganser swimming in water.

Description: The Spotted Sandpiper is a comon and widespread bird. It is generally not threatened, however it is vulnerable to habitat loss.
Caption: Two Spotted Sandpipers standing in water.

Description: The Surf Scoter is a species of duck that migrates to the Pacific coast of the United States, where it is vulnerable to oil spills and other pollution.
Caption: Two Surf Scoters swimming in water.
ImageLiscence: Free to copy and adapt with credit

Description: The Western Sandpiper is the smallest species of sandpipers and is unlikely to be significantly impacted by climate change.
Caption: Western Sandpiper standing on branches above water.
ImageLiscence: Free to copy and adapt with credit

Description: Racoons are medium-sized, nocturnal mammal. Nocturnal animals are chategorized by sleeping during the day and being active at night. Raccoons are considered to be very resilient animals.
Caption: Raccoon sitting in tree.

Description: Plants are non-animal organisms that use photosynthesis to make their own food. They produce a large amount of the world's oxygen during photosynthesis. Plants play a large role in supporting food chains.
Caption: Grasses.

Description: Wave attenuation is the decrease in wave intensity. Plants and other aquatic structures (e.g., coral reefs) play a large role in taming waves and violent storms that could damage shorelines.
Caption: Ocean waves.

Description: Microscopic organisms, or microbes, are tiny, single-celled organisms that cannot be seen with the naked eye. Microbes play an important role in nutrient cycling and there are more than 1 trillion different species, many of which have not yet been discovered.
Caption: Copepod.
ImageLiscence: Free to copy and adapt with credit

Description: Shoreline protection is the strengthening and stabilizing of coastal areas. Naturally, plants with deep roots can prevent erosion, enhancing shoreline protection.
Caption: Saltmarsh.

Description: Molluscs are invertebrate animals, meaning they do not have backbones. There are more than 85,000 species of molluscs today. Mollsucs are shell-forming animals and are vulnerable to ocean acidifcation and pollution.
Caption: Many mussels underwater.

Description: Carbon storage (also known as carbon sequestration) is the process of capturing and storing carbon. Carbon can be stored in plants, soils and other organic materials.
Caption: Salt marsh with vehicle in the background.

Description: Insects are invertebrate animals, meaning they do not have backbones. Insects are a class of arthropods with a hard external skeleton (known as the exoskeleton), a segmented body, and at least 3 pairs of legs. Some insects include ants, butterflies, mosquitoes and flies.
Caption: Dragonfly on branch.

Description: Water filtration is the process of removing and reducing the number of particles suspended in water. This helps improve water clarity by reducing sediment loads.
Caption: Mussels filtering water.

Description: Plankton are a diverse colletion of microscopic plants and animals that drift around in aquatic ecosystems. Phytoplankton is are tiny plants and Zooplankton are tiny animals that eat phytoplankton. Plankton form the base of aquatic food webs.
Caption: Microscopic image of plankton.

Description: Commercial fisheries are large-scale harvesting operations that target fish and other seafood for commercial profit. These fisheries do not occur in salt marshes. However, salt marshes and other coastal ecosystems like mangroves provide importance habitat and breeding grounds for many commercially important species.
Caption: Commercial fishing boat in a harbor.

Description: Crustaceans are invertebrate animals, meaning they do not have backbones. There are many different types of crustaceans, but they are generally categorixed by a hard exoskeleton, a segmented body and at least 4 pairs of jointed appendages ("legs" and "claws"). Crustaceans are vulnerable to over fishing, plastic pollution, habitat loss and ocean acidification. Ocean acidification occurs when there are changes in the chemical make up (specifically decreases in the pH due to increased carbon dioxide) of oceans, which can make it difficult for shell-builiding organisms to build their shells.
Caption: Crab standing in sand.

Description: Birdwatching, or birding, is a type of wildlife viewing, where people track, look and listen for birds. This can be done for recreation and/or citizen science.
Caption: Binoculars on bird guide.

Description: Fish are gill-bearing organisms that live in aquatic ecosystems. There are more than 28,000 species, some of which are of critical importance to fisheries and wildlife viewing. They vary in their vulnerability to disturbances, but can be impacted greatly by overfishing and warming waters.
Caption: Shiner Surfperch, one species of fish.
ImageLiscence: Free to copy and adapt with credit

Description: Waterfowl hunting is the activity of hunting ducks, geese or other water birds for fun and/or food.
Caption: Dog carrying waterfowl in grass.

Description: Birds are vertebrates charactereized by feathers, a beak, and wings. There are more than 9,000 species of birds with a wide array of fascinating behaviors. Like fish, they vary in their vulnerability but are generally impacted by pollution and habitat loss.
Caption: Flock of birds flying over water at sunset.

Description: Recreational fishing involves fishing for fun. This type of fishing can take place on small boats, on the shoreline, or on piers in salt marshes.
Caption: Fishing rod on pier over water.
